Module 1 – Design Patterns and Principles
1. SOLID Principles
Overview

SOLID is a set of five object-oriented design principles used to create clean, maintainable, scalable, and reusable software.

SOLID stands for:

S → Single Responsibility Principle (SRP)
O → Open Closed Principle (OCP)
L → Liskov Substitution Principle (LSP)
I → Interface Segregation Principle (ISP)
D → Dependency Inversion Principle (DIP)
A) Single Responsibility Principle (SRP)
Meaning

One class → One responsibility.

A class should have only one reason to change.

Example
class Student {}

class StudentService {
    void saveStudent(){}
}

class EmailService {
    void sendEmail(){}
}
Explanation
Student → stores student data
StudentService → handles saving
EmailService → handles email operations

Each class performs only one responsibility.

B) Open Closed Principle (OCP)
Meaning

Open for extension, Closed for modification.

Add new functionality without modifying existing code.

Example
interface Payment {
    void pay();
}

class UPI implements Payment {
    public void pay(){}
}

class Card implements Payment {
    public void pay(){}
}
Explanation

New payment methods can be added by creating new classes without changing existing code.

C) Liskov Substitution Principle (LSP)
Meaning

Child class should replace parent safely.

Subclass behavior should not break parent expectations.

Example
class Bird {}

class FlyingBird extends Bird {
    void fly(){}
}

class Penguin extends Bird {}
Explanation

Only birds that can actually fly should implement flying behavior.

D) Interface Segregation Principle (ISP)
Meaning

Do not force classes to implement unnecessary methods.

Use smaller and specific interfaces.

Example
interface Work {
    void work();
}

interface Eat {
    void eat();
}
Explanation

Classes implement only the interfaces they require.

E) Dependency Inversion Principle (DIP)
Meaning

Depend on abstraction, not concrete implementation.

Example
interface Database {
    void save();
}

class MySQL implements Database {
    public void save(){}
}

class Service {

    Database db;

    Service(Database db){
        this.db = db;
    }
}
Explanation

Service depends on Database interface instead of directly depending on MySQL.

Summary
Principle	Meaning
SRP	One class → One responsibility
OCP	Extend without modifying
LSP	Child should replace parent safely
ISP	Small and focused interfaces
DIP	Depend on abstraction
